    // For i, nums[i] > neighbor_prev AND nums[i] > neighbor_next.

    // The maximum number of peaks possible is floor(n/2) if we consider non-overlapping peaks,
    // but since we can modify values, we need to check a tighter bound.
    // If we have m peaks, say at indices i_1, i_2, ..., i_m.
    // For i_j to be a peak, it must be strictly greater than its two neighbors.
    // If we modify values, we can potentially create peaks at every index i,
    // provided n >= 3.
    // If n=2, [a, b].
